<br>
Let's put aside the war, and which party controls congress, and all that shit for a minute. In general, very high level terms, what direction would you like to see the country headed, in terms of our position in international affairs. I'll try to make each position in a positive stance, and include some statements here summarizing them to see which one's you most agree with. (The actual choice lines are too short, so I'll expand on them and explain them here.)<br>
<br>
1. Strict Isolationism - &quot;Fuck the rest of those countries. We have way more than enough of our own problems that need solving right here in America. In terms of the military, we pull them all back to North America where we could defend this continent with a considerably smaller and less expensive force. The only time we send our boys anywhere is when we get attacked first. And if we are, we go in full bore and blow the bastards to hell and come right back home. Let them pick up the pieces themselves. They shouldn't have fucked with us in the first place. Ok, we'll probably take care of Canada and Mexico, but only because we don't need anybody else's armies camped out that close to us. Pull out of the UN entirely and let them handle their own problems.&quot;<br>
<br>
2. NATO Based Cooperation - &quot;We can have some international cooperation, but let's keep it to the countries that we have the most in common with. We can have lots of trade and mutual military support with North American and Western European nations, and we'll even help defend them if they get attacked. Scrap the UN and have NATO, under our majority leadership, be the guiding force for international disputes and affairs. We've never really understood the cultures in Africa, the Middle East and Asia, so we stay the fuck out. Taking care of our countries is enough of a job.&quot;<br>
<br>
3. Guardian of the World - &quot;As the world's only superpower and an example of democracy and individual freedom, it's our responsibility to help others everywhere. Unfortunately, the UN has proved to be inadequate to the task. Like it or not, we need to be the &quot;world's policeman&quot; because frankly, somebody has to do it. We go where we're needed as we see fit to eliminate despots, warlike dictators and human rights abuses, end starvation and spread technological advances. Some countries may not like it, but they'll thank us for it later. The UN can stick around in an advisory capacity for open international discussions, but we're going to be calling the shots, make no mistake.&quot;<br>
<br>
4.  Global Government Model - &quot;We need to take an active role in international affairs, but as an equal partner with all the other citizens of the planet. We should go and help out where needed, but never without a majority consent of the other countries of the world, who should take a larger role and responsibility in helping us do all this work. Each should contribute, both in terms of military force, and economic aid, according to their size and ability. The UN needs to be totally revamped to change it from an advisory body to a true central government, with the military might to back up what is decided there. Our troops, except when defending attacks on our own borders, will be used at the discretion of the UN, alongside troops from all other countries, to handle matters of military incursion when they arise.&quot;<br>
<br>
